pr_title: fix: support add an app from git repository
pr_body:
Signed-off-by: Zixuan Liu <nodeces@gmail.com>

#### Description

The feature supports add an app from git respository.

example:
```
jx add app https://github.com/jenkins-x-apps/jx-app-kubeless.git
```

pr_body:
Signed-off-by: Zixuan Liu <nodeces@gmail.com>

6. If the PR is unfinished, see how to mark it: https://git.k8s.io/community/contributors/guide/pull-requests.md#marking-unfinished-pull-requests

#### Description
Due to windows file struct, We cannot found `/bin/sh` in Windows. 

#### Special notes for the reviewer(s)


#### Which issue this PR fixes

fixes https://github.com/jenkins-x/jx/issues/7035

<!--
optional, in `fixes #<issue number>(, fixes #<issue_number>, ...)` format, will close that issue when PR gets merged
-->
pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 413629634, 'comment_body': 'I wonder whether it would be safe to always use "sh". This really should work on any OS. @abayer wdyt?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 23, 8, 45, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 413739864, 'comment_body': 'Seems possible? I‚Äôm a little wary, but I may just be excessively conservative.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 23, 11, 34, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'abayer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 413783509, 'comment_body': 'Maybe we can use `cmd `.  WDYT?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 23, 12, 44, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 414352142, 'comment_body': "not sure about `cmd`. How would that work? I was just trying to about the special case for Windows. A simple 'sh' should work on macOS and Linux as well. But maybe @abayer is right and we should be a bit more conservative here.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 24, 7, 20, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 414352560, 'comment_body': "I don't have a way atm to verify that this actually works on Windows, so I guess we just see what happens.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 24, 7, 21, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}]

The default implementation would still read from the file system, but for testing we can return arbitrary data. 

WDYT?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 26, 8, 50, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 398405574, 'comment_body': 'Also, one could use the string returned by `getFileContent` and split it at '\n' and pass the slice then to `util.ExtractKeyValuePairs` which returns a map of key/value pairs. Then one just can check for the "PRETTY_NAME" key. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 26, 8, 53, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 398405678, 'comment_body': 'üëç ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 26, 8, 53, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 398482733, 'comment_body': "don't use ALL_CAPS in Go names; use CamelCase", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 26, 10, 57, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'houndci-bot', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 398482736, 'comment_body': 'comment on exported type DefaultReleaseFileGetter should be of the form "DefaultReleaseFileGetter ..." pr_body:
Signed-off-by: Zixuan Liu <nodeces@gmail.com>

#### Which issue this PR fixes

fixes #6936 

<!--
optional, in `fixes #<issue number>(, fixes #<issue_number>, ...)` format, will close that issue when PR gets merged
-->
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 395031869, 'comment_body': "I don't think this is quite correct. If you look at the docs for this function, then you see that the intend is to walk up the filesystem to find the requirements file there. I am not saying this is good behaviour, just how it is. The reason for this is to be able to execute individual jx boot step in sub-directories of the requirements/dev repository. 

I am pretty sure that this change will brake this behaviour. 

To do what you are after, I think we need to split or at least pull out the file existence check from `LoadRequirementsConfigFile`. You need to be able to distinguish between the file not existing at all and the file not loadable due to a syntax error.

I think it would be great to add some tests around this as well. Should be quite straight forward, since _install_requirements_test.go_ already exists. One can just add a couple of more test scenarios to the _test_data_ directory. 

WDYT?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 19, 13, 40, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395054739, 'comment_body': 'Thank you for your review! I know how to fix it.

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 19, 14, 12, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395102918, 'comment_body': 'Resolved.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 19, 15, 14, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395124155, 'comment_body': "Not sure whether an explicit `util.FileExists` would be better here. It might mean that we check for existence twice, but I don't think that matters. This is really now depending on an implementation detail and there is really no guarantee that `LoadRequirementsConfigFile` is going to pass up the `PathError`. It could for example wrap the error.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 19, 15, 42, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395137549, 'comment_body': 'I think `errors.Wrap` is used. We need to call `errors.Unwrap`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 19, 16, 0, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395168153, 'comment_body': 'Fixed', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 19, 16, 43, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395505016, 'comment_body': 'I still would feel more comfortable if we prior to `config, err := LoadRequirementsConfigFile(fileName)` do an explicit file existence check:

```go
        absolute = filepath.Dir(absolute)
	exists, err := util.FileExists(fileName)
	if err != nil {
		return nil, "", err
	}

        if !exist {
            continue
       }

       config, err := LoadRequirementsConfigFile(fileName)
	if err == nil {
		return nil, "", err
	}
```

Something along these lines. I think that is easier to understand and it does also not rely on an implementation detail of `LoadRequirementsConfigFile`, namely that it does return the PathError directly. It might as well wrap it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 8, 57, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395506030, 'comment_body': "Let's put this test into its own test function and give it a name which tells what we test, something like `Test_LoadRequirementsConfig_load_invalid_yaml`

I also think we should not only assert that an error is returned, but also that is the error we expect. For example by looking at the error message.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 8, 59, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395506100, 'comment_body': 'newlines missing', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 8, 59, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395517995, 'comment_body': 'I feel great!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 9, 24, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395546048, 'comment_body': "Github ignored line 36. actually, I've added newlines.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 10, 22, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nodece', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395720069, 'comment_body': 'üëç ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 15, 37, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 395720435, 'comment_body': ':+1', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 20, 15, 38, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hferentschik', 'type': 'User'}]
